<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-01-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-01-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="32" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d32">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–1149: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-01-11">January 11,
                                1949</date>.<lb/>[Received January 11—5:52 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>85. Vernacular press January 10 reports telegram appealing for peace sent
                            to Generalissimo and Mao Tse-tung by All China Federation of Shipping
                            Guilds signed by Tu Yueh-sheng, chairman. Sent Nanking 67, repeated
                            Department 85.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>